# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: partial-evaluation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:partial-evaluation/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In computing, **memoization** or **memoisation** is an optimization technique used primarily to speed up computer programs.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] It works by storing the results of expensive calls to pure functions, so that these results can be returned quickly should the same inputs occur again.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] It is a type of caching, normally implemented using a hash table, and a typical example of a space–time tradeoff, where the runtime of a program is reduced by increasing its memory usage.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Memoization can be implemented in any programming language, though some languages have built-in support that make it easy for the programmer to memoize a function, and others memoize certain functions by default.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Memoization has also been used in other contexts (and for purposes other than speed gains), such as in simple mutually recursive descent parsing.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In the context of some logic programming languages, memoization is also known as tabling.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The term *memoization* was coined by Donald Michie in 1968 and is derived from the Latin word *memorandum* ('to be remembered'), usually truncated as *memo* in American English, and thus carries the meaning of 'turning [the results of] a function into something to be remembered'.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] While *memoization* might be confused with *memorization* (because they are etymological cognates), *memoization* has a specialized meaning in computing.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] A memoized function, when called with a given set of inputs for the first time, stores the inputs along with the computed results.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Upon subsequent calls with remembered inputs, the function returns the remembered results rather than recomputing them, thus eliminating the cost of a recomputation.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The set of remembered associations may be a fixed-size set controlled by a replacement algorithm or a fixed set, depending on the nature of the function and its use.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] A function can only be memoized if it is referentially transparent; that is, only if calling the function has exactly the same effect as replacing that function call with its return value.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] (Special case exceptions to this restriction exist, however.) While related to lookup tables, since memoization often uses such tables in its implementation, memoization populates its cache of results transparently on the fly, rather than needing them to be supplied in advance.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Memoized functions are optimized for *speed* in exchange for a higher use of computer memory *space*.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The time/space "cost" of algorithms has a specific name in computing: *computational complexity*.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] All functions have a computational complexity in *time* (i.e. they take time to execute) and in *space*.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Although a space–time tradeoff occurs (i.e., space used is speed gained), this differs from some other optimizations that involve time-space trade-off, such as strength reduction, in that memoization is a run-time rather than compile-time optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] For every integer *n* such that `*n* ≥ 0`, the final result of the function `factorial` is invariant; if invoked as `*x* = factorial(3)`, the result is such that *x* will *always* be assigned the value 6.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The non-memoized implementation above, given the nature of the recursive algorithm involved, would require *n + 1* invocations of `factorial` to arrive at a result, and each of these invocations, in turn, has an associated cost in the time it takes the function to return the value computed.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The cost to set up the recursive call stack frame.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The cost to multiply the result of the recursive call to `factorial` by *n*.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The cost to store the return result so that it may be used by the calling context.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In a non-memoized implementation, *every* top-level call to `factorial` includes the cumulative cost of steps 2 through 6 proportional to the initial value of *n*.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] If it is then called with a number greater than 5, such as 7, only 2 recursive calls will be made (7 and 6), and the value for 5! will have been stored from the previous call.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In this way, memoization allows a function to become more time-efficient the more often it is called, thus resulting in eventual overall speed-up.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] An extreme example of memoization is the Singleton pattern, specifically the implementation of its getter — a function that creates an object upon the first invocation, caches the instance, and returns the same object on all subsequent invocations.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Memoization is heavily used in compilers for functional programming languages, which often use call by name evaluation strategy.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] To avoid overhead with calculating argument values, compilers for these languages heavily use auxiliary functions called thunks to compute the argument values, and memoize these functions to avoid repeated calculations.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] While memoization may be added to functions *internally* and *explicitly* by a computer programmer in much the same way the above memoized version of `factorial` is implemented, referentially transparent functions may also be automatically memoized *externally*.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The techniques employed by Peter Norvig have application not only in Common Lisp (the language in which his paper demonstrated automatic memoization), but also in various other programming languages.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Applications of automatic memoization have also been formally explored in the study of term rewriting and artificial intelligence.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In programming languages where functions are first-class objects (such as Lua, Python, or Perl), automatic memoization can be implemented by replacing (at run-time) a function with its calculated value once a value has been calculated for a given set of parameters.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The function that does this value-for-function-object replacement can generically wrap any referentially transparent function.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In order to call an automatically memoized version of `factorial` using the above strategy, rather than calling `factorial` directly, code invokes `memoized-call(factorial)(*n*)`.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Each such call first checks to see if a holder array has been allocated to store results, and if not, attaches that array.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] If no entry exists at the position `values[arguments]` (where `arguments` are used as the key of the associative array), a *real* call is made to `factorial` with the supplied arguments.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Finally, the entry in the array at the key position is returned to the caller.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The above strategy requires *explicit* wrapping at each call to a function that is to be memoized.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In those languages that allow closures, memoization can be effected *implicitly* via a functor factory that returns a wrapped memoized function object in a decorator pattern.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The above example assumes that the function `factorial` has already been defined *before* the call to `construct-memoized-functor` is made.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] From this point forward, `memfact(*n*)` is called whenever the factorial of *n* is desired.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] When a top-down parser tries to parse an ambiguous input with respect to an ambiguous context-free grammar (CFG), it may need an exponential number of steps (with respect to the length of the input) to try all alternatives of the CFG in order to produce all possible parse trees.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] This eventually would require exponential memory space.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The basic idea in Norvig's approach is that when a parser is applied to the input, the result is stored in a memotable for subsequent reuse if the same parser is ever reapplied to the same input.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Richard Frost and Barbara Szydlowski also used memoization to reduce the exponential time complexity of parser combinators, describing the result as a memoizing purely functional top-down backtracking language processor.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Frost showed that basic memoized parser combinators can be used as building blocks to construct complex parsers as executable specifications of CFGs.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Memoization was again explored in the context of parsing in 1995 by Mark Johnson and Jochen Dörre.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In 2002, it was examined in considerable depth by Bryan Ford in the form called packrat parsing.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In 2007, Frost, Hafiz and Callaghan described a top-down parsing algorithm that uses memoization for refraining redundant computations to accommodate any form of ambiguous CFG in polynomial time (Θ(n4) for left-recursive grammars and Θ(n3) for non left-recursive grammars).
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Their top-down parsing algorithm also requires polynomial space for potentially exponential ambiguous parse trees by 'compact representation' and 'local ambiguities grouping'.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Their compact representation is comparable with Tomita's compact representation of bottom-up parsing.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Frost, Hafiz and Callaghan also described the implementation of the algorithm in PADL’08 as a set of higher-order functions (called parser combinators) in Haskell, which enables the construction of directly executable specifications of CFGs as language processors.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The importance of their polynomial algorithm's power to accommodate ‘any form of ambiguous CFG’ with top-down parsing is vital with respect to the syntax and semantics analysis during natural language processing.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The X-SAIGA site has more about the algorithm and implementation details.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] While Norvig increased the *power* of the parser through memoization, the augmented parser was still as time complex as Earley's algorithm, which demonstrates a case of the use of memoization for something other than speed optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Johnson and Dörre demonstrate another such non-speed related application of memoization: the use of memoization to delay linguistic constraint resolution to a point in a parse where sufficient information has been accumulated to resolve those constraints.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] By contrast, in the speed optimization application of memoization, Ford demonstrated that memoization could guarantee that parsing expression grammars could parse in linear time even those languages that resulted in worst-case backtracking behavior.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The key concept here is inherent in the phrase **again descends into *X***.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] The process of looking forward, failing, backing up, and then retrying the next alternative is known in parsing as backtracking, and it is primarily backtracking that presents opportunities for memoization in parsing.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] Let the return value of the function `RuleAcceptsSomeInput` be the length of the input accepted by `Rule`, or 0 if that rule does not accept any input at that offset in the string.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In the above example, one or *many* descents into *X* may occur, allowing for strings such as *xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxbd*.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] In fact, there may be *any number* of *x*'s before the *b*.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] While the call to S must recursively descend into X as many times as there are *x*'s, *B* will never have to descend into X at all, since the return value of `RuleAcceptsSomeInput(*X*, 0, *xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxbd*)` will be 16 (in this particular case).
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] For the same reason, memoized parser algorithms that generate calls to external code (sometimes called a semantic action routine) when a rule matches must use some scheme to ensure that such rules are invoked in a predictable order.
[src:partial-evaluation/memoization] This effect can be mitigated by explicit selection of those rules the parser will memoize.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] The second approach is dynamic execution of expressions that contain programming commands, often composed from strings, but can also be from other methods using arguments or context, like JavaScript.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Thus, "programs can write programs." Although both approaches can be used in the same language, most languages tend to lean toward one or the other.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] The third approach is to step outside the language entirely.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] General purpose program transformation systems such as compilers, which accept language descriptions and carry out arbitrary transformations on those languages, are direct implementations of general metaprogramming.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] This allows metaprogramming to be applied to virtually any target language without regard to whether that target language has any metaprogramming abilities of its own.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] One can see this at work with Scheme and how it allows tackling some limits faced in C by using constructs that are part of the Scheme language to extend C.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Lisp is probably the quintessential language with metaprogramming facilities, both because of its historical precedence and because of the simplicity and power of its metaprogramming.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] In Lisp metaprogramming, the unquote operator (typically a comma) introduces code that is evaluated at program definition time rather than at run time.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] The metaprogramming language is thus identical to the host programming language, and existing Lisp routines can be directly reused for metaprogramming if desired.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] This approach has been implemented in other languages by incorporating an interpreter in the program, which works directly with the program's data.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] There are implementations of this kind for some common high-level languages, such as RemObjects’ Pascal Script for Object Pascal.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] This script (or program) generates a new 993-line program that prints out the numbers 1–992.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] This is only an illustration of how to use code to write more code; it is not the most efficient way to print out a list of numbers.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Nonetheless, a programmer can write and execute this metaprogram in less than a minute, and will have generated over 1000 lines of code in that amount of time.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] A quine is a special kind of metaprogram that produces its own source code as its output.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Quines are generally of recreational or theoretical interest only.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Not all metaprogramming involves generative programming.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] One style of generative approach is to employ domain-specific languages (DSLs).
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] One usage of metaprogramming is to instrument programs in order to do dynamic program analysis.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Some argue that there is a sharp learning curve to make complete use of metaprogramming features.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Since metaprogramming gives more flexibility and configurability at runtime, misuse or incorrect use of metaprogramming can result in unwarranted and unexpected errors that can be extremely difficult to debug to an average developer.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] It can introduce risks in the system and make it more vulnerable if not used with care.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Some of the common problems, which can occur due to wrong use of metaprogramming are inability of the compiler to identify missing configuration parameters, invalid or incorrect data can result in unknown exception or different results.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Due to this, some believe that only high-skilled developers should work on developing features which exercise metaprogramming in a language or platform and average developers must learn how to use these features as part of convention.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] The IBM/360 and derivatives had powerful macro assembler facilities that were often used to generate complete assembly language programs or sections of programs (for different operating systems for instance).
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Macros provided with CICS transaction processing system had assembler macros that generated COBOL statements as a pre-processing step.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Other assemblers, such as MASM, also support macros.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] Use of dependent types allows proving that generated code is never invalid.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] However, this approach is leading-edge and rarely found outside of research programming languages.
[src:partial-evaluation/metaprogramming] The list of notable metaprogramming systems is maintained at List of program transformation systems.
[src:partial-evaluation/multi-stage-programming] In MSP languages, expressions are qualified by notation that specifies the phase at which they are to be evaluated.
[src:partial-evaluation/multi-stage-programming] By allowing the specialization of a program at run-time, MSP can optimize the performance of programs: it can be considered as a form of partial evaluation that performs computations at compile-time as a trade-off to increase the speed of run-time processing.
[src:partial-evaluation/multi-stage-programming] Multi-stage programming languages support constructs similar to the Lisp construct of quotation and `eval`, except that scoping rules are taken into account.
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] In computing, **partial evaluation** is a technique for several different types of program optimization by specialization.
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] The most straightforward application is to produce new programs that run faster than the originals while being guaranteed to behave in the same way.
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] where $I_{\text{static}}$ , the *static data*, is the part of the input data known at compile time.
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] The act of partial evaluation is said to "residualize" ${\texttt {prog}}$ to ${\texttt {prog}}^{*}$ .
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] A particularly interesting example of the use of partial evaluation, first described in the 1970s by Yoshihiko Futamura, is when ${\texttt {prog}}$ is an interpreter for a programming language.
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] In this case ${\texttt {prog}}^{*}$ is effectively a compiled version of $I_{\text{static}}$ .
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] Specializing the specializer for the interpreter (as applied in #1), yielding a compiler.
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] Specializing the specializer for itself (as applied in #2), yielding a tool that can convert any interpreter to an equivalent compiler.
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] They were described by Futamura in Japanese in 1971 and in English in 1983.
[src:partial-evaluation/partial-evaluation] PyPy's RPython and GraalVM's Truffle framework are examples of real-world JIT compilers that implement Futamura's first projection.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In computer science, **program optimization**, **code optimization**, or **software optimization** is the process of modifying a software system to make some aspect of it work more efficiently or use fewer resources.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In general, a computer program may be optimized so that it executes more rapidly, or to make it capable of operating with less memory storage or other resources, or draw less power.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Although the term "optimization" is derived from "optimum", achieving a truly optimal system is rare in practice, which is referred to as superoptimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimization typically focuses on improving a system with respect to a specific quality metric rather than making it universally optimal.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] This often leads to trade-offs, where enhancing one metric may come at the expense of another.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] One frequently cited example is the space–time tradeoff, where reducing a program’s execution time can increase its memory consumption.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Conversely, in scenarios where memory is limited, engineers might prioritize a slower algorithm to conserve space.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] There is rarely a single design that can excel in all situations, requiring programmers to prioritize attributes most relevant to the application at hand.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Metrics for software include throughput, latency, volatile memory usage, persistent storage, internet usage, energy consumption, and hardware wear and tear.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Furthermore, achieving absolute optimization often demands disproportionate effort relative to the benefits gained.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Consequently, optimization processes usually slow once sufficient improvements are achieved.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Fortunately, significant gains often occur early in the optimization process, making it practical to stop before reaching diminishing returns.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimization can occur at a number of levels.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Typically the higher levels have greater impact, and are harder to change later on in a project, requiring significant changes or a complete rewrite if they need to be changed.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Thus optimization can typically proceed via refinement from higher to lower, with initial gains being larger and achieved with less work, and later gains being smaller and requiring more work.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] However, in some cases overall performance depends on performance of very low-level portions of a program, and small changes at a late stage or early consideration of low-level details can have outsized impact.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Typically some consideration is given to efficiency throughout a project – though this varies significantly – but major optimization is often considered a refinement to be done late, if ever.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] On longer-running projects there are typically cycles of optimization, where improving one area reveals limitations in another, and these are typically curtailed when performance is acceptable or gains become too small or costly.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Best practices for optimization during iterative development cycles include continuous monitoring for performance issues coupled with regular performance testing.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] The degree to which performance changes between prototype and production system, and how amenable it is to optimization, can be a significant source of uncertainty and risk.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] At the highest level, the design may be optimized to make best use of the available resources, given goals, constraints, and expected use/load.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] The architectural design of a system overwhelmingly affects its performance.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For example, a system that is network latency-bound (where network latency is the main constraint on overall performance) would be optimized to minimize network trips, ideally making a single request (or no requests, as in a push protocol) rather than multiple roundtrips.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Choice of platform and programming language occur at this level, and changing them frequently requires a complete rewrite, though a modular system may allow rewrite of only some component – for example, for a Python program one may rewrite performance-critical sections in C.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In a distributed system, choice of architecture (client-server, peer-to-peer, etc.) occurs at the design level, and may be difficult to change, particularly if all components cannot be replaced in sync (e.g., old clients).
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Given an overall design, a good choice of efficient algorithms and data structures, and efficient implementation of these algorithms and data structures comes next.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] After design, the choice of algorithms and data structures affects efficiency more than any other aspect of the program.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Changes in data structures mapped to a database may require schema migration and other complex software or infrastructure changes.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For algorithms, this primarily consists of ensuring that algorithms are constant O(1), logarithmic O(log *n*), linear O(*n*), or in some cases log-linear O(*n* log *n*) in the input (both in space and time).
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Algorithms with quadratic complexity O(*n*2) fail to scale, and even linear algorithms cause problems if repeatedly called, and are typically replaced with constant or logarithmic if possible.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Beyond asymptotic order of growth, the constant factors matter: an asymptotically slower algorithm may be faster or smaller (because simpler) than an asymptotically faster algorithm when they are both faced with small input, which may be the case that occurs in reality.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Often a hybrid algorithm will provide the best performance, due to this tradeoff changing with size.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] A general technique to improve performance is to avoid work.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] A good example is the use of a fast path for common cases, improving performance by avoiding unnecessary work.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For example, using a simple text layout algorithm for Latin text, only switching to a complex layout algorithm for complex scripts, such as Devanagari.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Another important technique is caching, particularly memoization, which avoids redundant computations.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Because of the importance of caching, there are often many levels of caching in a system, which can cause problems from memory use, and correctness issues from stale caches.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Beyond general algorithms and their implementation on an abstract machine, concrete source code level choices can make a significant difference.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For example, on early C compilers, `while (true)` was slower than `for (;;)` for an unconditional loop, because `while (true)` evaluated `true` and then had a conditional jump which tested if it was true, while `for (;;)` had an unconditional jump.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Some optimizations (such as this one) can nowadays be performed by optimizing compilers.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] This depends on the source language, the target machine language, and the compiler, and can be both difficult to understand or predict and changes over time; this is a key place where understanding of compilers and machine code can improve performance.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Loop-invariant code motion and return value optimization are examples of optimizations that reduce the need for auxiliary variables and can even result in faster performance by avoiding round-about optimizations.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Source-based software distribution systems such as BSD's Ports and Gentoo's Portage can take advantage of this form of optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Use of an optimizing compiler with optimizations enabled tends to ensure that the executable program is optimized at least as much as the compiler can reasonable perform.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] See Optimizing compiler for more details.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] At the lowest level, writing code using an assembly language, designed for a particular hardware platform can produce the most efficient and compact code if the programmer takes advantage of the full repertoire of machine instructions.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Many operating systems used on embedded systems have been traditionally written in assembler code for this reason.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Programs (other than very small programs) are seldom written from start to finish in assembly due to the time and cost involved.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Most are compiled down from a high level language to assembly and hand optimized from there.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] When efficiency and size are less important large parts may be written in a high-level language.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] With more modern optimizing compilers and the greater complexity of recent CPUs, it is harder to write more efficient code than what the compiler generates, and few projects need this "ultimate" optimization step.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Much of the code written today is intended to run on as many machines as possible.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] As a consequence, programmers and compilers don't always take advantage of the more efficient instructions provided by newer CPUs or quirks of older models.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Additionally, assembly code tuned for a particular processor without using such instructions might still be suboptimal on a different processor, expecting a different tuning of the code.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Typically today rather than writing in assembly language, programmers will use a disassembler to analyze the output of a compiler and change the high-level source code so that it can be compiled more efficiently, or understand why it is inefficient.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Just-in-time compilers can produce customized machine code based on run-time data, at the cost of compilation overhead.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] This technique dates to the earliest regular expression engines, and has become widespread with Java HotSpot and V8 for JavaScript.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In some cases adaptive optimization may be able to perform run time optimization exceeding the capability of static compilers by dynamically adjusting parameters according to the actual input or other factors.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Profile-guided optimization is an ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation optimization technique based on run time profiles, and is similar to a static "average case" analog of the dynamic technique of adaptive optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Self-modifying code can alter itself in response to run time conditions in order to optimize code; this was more common in assembly language programs.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Some CPU designs can perform some optimizations at run time.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Some examples include out-of-order execution, speculative execution, instruction pipelines, and branch predictors.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Compilers can help the program take advantage of these CPU features, for example through instruction scheduling.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Code optimization can be also broadly categorized as platform-dependent and platform-independent techniques.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] While the latter ones are effective on most or all platforms, platform-dependent techniques use specific properties of one platform, or rely on parameters depending on the single platform or even on the single processor.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Writing or producing different versions of the same code for different processors might therefore be needed.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For instance, in the case of compile-level optimization, platform-independent techniques are generic techniques (such as loop unrolling, reduction in function calls, memory efficient routines, reduction in conditions, etc.), that impact most CPU architectures in a similar way.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] A great example of platform-independent optimization has been shown with inner for loop, where it was observed that a loop with an inner for loop performs more computations per unit time than a loop without it or one with an inner while loop.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Generally, these serve to reduce the total instruction path length required to complete the program and/or reduce total memory usage during the process.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Computational tasks can be performed in several different ways with varying efficiency.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] A more efficient version with equivalent functionality is known as a strength reduction.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] The optimization, sometimes performed automatically by an optimizing compiler, is to select a method (algorithm) that is more computationally efficient, while retaining the same functionality.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] See algorithmic efficiency for a discussion of some of these techniques.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] However, a significant improvement in performance can often be achieved by removing extraneous functionality.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimization is not always an obvious or intuitive process.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In the example above, the "optimized" version might actually be slower than the original version if *N* were sufficiently small and the particular hardware happens to be much faster at performing addition and looping operations than multiplication and division.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In some cases, however, optimization relies on using more elaborate algorithms, making use of "special cases" and special "tricks" and performing complex trade-offs.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] A "fully optimized" program might be more difficult to comprehend and hence may contain more faults than unoptimized versions.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Beyond eliminating obvious antipatterns, some code level optimizations decrease maintainability.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimization will generally focus on improving just one or two aspects of performance: execution time, memory usage, disk space, bandwidth, power consumption or some other resource.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] This will usually require a trade-off – where one factor is optimized at the expense of others.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For example, increasing the size of cache improves run time performance, but also increases the memory consumption.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Other common trade-offs include code clarity and conciseness.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] There are instances where the programmer performing the optimization must decide to make the software better for some operations but at the cost of making other operations less efficient.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] These trade-offs may sometimes be of a non-technical nature – such as when a competitor has published a benchmark result that must be beaten in order to improve commercial success but comes perhaps with the burden of making normal usage of the software less efficient.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Such changes are sometimes jokingly referred to as *pessimizations*.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimization may include finding a bottleneck in a system – a component that is the limiting factor on performance.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In terms of code, this will often be a hot spot – a critical part of the code that is the primary consumer of the needed resource – though it can be another factor, such as I/O latency or network bandwidth.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In computer science, resource consumption often follows a form of power law distribution, and the Pareto principle can be applied to resource optimization by observing that 80% of the resources are typically used by 20% of the operations.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In software engineering, it is often a better approximation that 90% of the execution time of a computer program is spent executing 10% of the code (known as the 90/10 law in this context).
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] A performance profiler can be used to narrow down decisions about which functionality fits which conditions.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Performance profiling therefore provides not only bottleneck detection but rather a variety of methods for optimization guidance.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Empirical algorithmics is the practice of using empirical methods, typically performance profiling, to study the behavior of algorithms, for developer understanding that may lead to human-planned optimizations.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Profile-guided optimization is the machine-driven use of profiling data as input to an optimizing compiler or interpreter.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Some programming languages are associated with tools for profile-guided optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Some performance profiling methods emphasize enhancements based on cache utilization.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Other benefits of performance profiling may include improved resource management and an enhanced user experience.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In some cases, adding more memory can help to make a program run faster.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For example, a filtering program will commonly read each line and filter and output that line immediately.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] This only uses enough memory for one line, but performance is typically poor, due to the latency of each disk read.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Caching the result is similarly effective, though also requiring larger memory use.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Typically, optimization involves choosing the best overall algorithms and data structures.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Frequently, algorithmic improvements can cause performance improvements of several orders of magnitude instead of micro-optimizations, which rarely improve performance by more than a few percent.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] If one waits to optimize until the end of the development cycle, then changing the algorithm could require a significant rewrite.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Frequently, micro-optimization can reduce readability and complicate programs or systems.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] That can make programs more difficult to maintain and debug.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] "Premature optimization" is often used as a rallying cry against all optimization in all situations for all purposes.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Frequently, Clean Code causes code to be more complicated than simpler more efficient code.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] When deciding what to optimize, Amdahl's Law should be used to proritize parts based on the actual time spent in a certain part, which is not always clear from looking at the code without a performance analysis.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In practice, it is often necessary to keep performance goals in mind when first designing software, yet programmers must balance various tradeoffs.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Development cost is significant, and hardware is fast.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Modern compilers are efficient enough that the intended performance increases sometimes fail to materialize.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Since compilers perform many automatic optimizations, some optimizations may yield an identical executable.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Also, sometimes hardware may reduce the impact of micro-optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For example, hardware may cache data that is cached at a software level.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimization during code development using macros takes on different forms in different languages.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In some procedural languages, such as C and C++, macros are implemented using token substitution.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Nowadays, inline functions can be used as a type safe alternative in many cases.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In both cases, the inlined function body can then undergo further compile-time optimizations by the compiler, including constant folding, which may move some computations to compile time.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In many functional programming languages, macros are implemented using parse-time substitution of parse trees/abstract syntax trees, which it is claimed makes them safer to use.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Since in many cases interpretation is used, that is one way to ensure that such computations are only performed at parse-time, and sometimes the only way.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Lisp originated this style of macro, and such macros are often called "Lisp-like macros".
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] A similar effect can be achieved by using template metaprogramming in C++.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In both cases, work is moved to compile-time.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Additionally, C macros do not directly support recursion or iteration, so are not Turing complete.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] As with any optimization, however, it is often difficult to predict where such tools will have the most impact before a project is complete.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimization can be automated by compilers or performed by programmers.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Gains are usually limited for local optimization, and larger for global optimizations.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Usually, the most powerful optimization is to find a superior algorithm.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimizing a whole system is usually undertaken by programmers because it is too complex for automated optimizers.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In this situation, programmers or system administrators explicitly change code so that the overall system performs better.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Although it can produce better efficiency, it is far more expensive than automated optimizations.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Since many parameters influence the program performance, the program optimization space is large.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Meta-heuristics and machine learning are used to address the complexity of program optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Use a profiler (or performance analyzer) to find the sections of the program that are taking the most resources – the *bottleneck*.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Programmers sometimes believe they have a clear idea of where the bottleneck is, but intuition is frequently wrong.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimizing an unimportant piece of code will typically do little to help the overall performance.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] When the bottleneck is localized, optimization usually starts with a rethinking of the algorithm used in the program.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] More often than not, a particular algorithm can be specifically tailored to a particular problem, yielding better performance than a generic algorithm.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For example, the task of sorting a huge list of items is usually done with a quicksort routine, which is one of the most efficient generic algorithms.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] But if some characteristic of the items is exploitable (for example, they are already arranged in some particular order), a different method can be used, or even a custom-made sort routine.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] After the programmer is reasonably sure that the best algorithm is selected, code optimization can start.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Loops can be unrolled (for lower loop overhead, although this can often lead to *lower* speed if it overloads the CPU cache), data types as small as possible can be used, integer arithmetic can be used instead of floating-point, and so on.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Performance bottlenecks can be due to language limitations rather than algorithms or data structures used in the program.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Sometimes, a critical part of the program can be re-written in a different programming language that gives more direct access to the underlying machine.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] For example, it is common for very high-level languages like Python to have modules written in C for greater speed.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Programs already written in C can have modules written in assembly.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Programs written in D can use the inline assembler.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Rewriting sections "pays off" in these circumstances because of a general "rule of thumb" known as the 90/10 law, which states that 90% of the time is spent in 10% of the code, and only 10% of the time in the remaining 90% of the code.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] So, putting intellectual effort into optimizing just a small part of the program can have a huge effect on the overall speed – if the correct part(s) can be located.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Manual optimization sometimes has the side effect of undermining readability.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Thus code optimizations should be carefully documented (preferably using in-line comments), and their effect on future development evaluated.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] The program that performs an automated optimization is called an **optimizer**.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Most optimizers are embedded in compilers and operate during compilation.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimizers can often tailor the generated code to specific processors.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Today, automated optimizations are almost exclusively limited to compiler optimization.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] However, because compiler optimizations are usually limited to a fixed set of rather general optimizations, there is considerable demand for optimizers which can accept descriptions of problem and language-specific optimizations, allowing an engineer to specify custom optimizations.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Tools that accept descriptions of optimizations are called program transformation systems and are beginning to be applied to real software systems such as C++.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Some high-level languages (Eiffel, Esterel) optimize their programs by using an intermediate language.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Grid computing or distributed computing aims to optimize the whole system, by moving tasks from computers with high usage to computers with idle time.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Sometimes, the time taken to undertake optimization therein itself may be an issue.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimizing existing code usually does not add new features, and worse, it might add new bugs in previously working code (as any change might).
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Because manually optimized code might sometimes have less "readability" than unoptimized code, optimization might impact maintainability of it as well.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Optimization comes at a price and it is important to be sure that the investment is worthwhile.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] An automatic optimizer (or optimizing compiler, a program that performs code optimization) may itself have to be optimized, either to further improve the efficiency of its target programs or else speed up its own operation.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] A compilation performed with optimization "turned on" usually takes longer, although this is usually only a problem when programs are quite large.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] In particular, for just-in-time compilers the performance of the run time compile component, executing together with its target code, is the key to improving overall execution speed.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Sometimes, "optimizations" may hurt performance.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Concurrency and parallelism cause significant overhead performance cost and possibly increased energy usage.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Keep in mind that C code rarely uses explicit multiprocessing, yet it typically runs faster than any other programming language.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Disk caching, paging, and swapping often cause significant increases to energy usage and hardware wear and tear.
[src:partial-evaluation/program-optimization] Running processes in the background to improve startup time slows down all other processes.
